---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '../components/PageHeader.astro';
import SectionDivider from '../components/SectionDivider.astro';
import PullQuote from '../components/PullQuote.astro';
import SourceLink from '../components/SourceLink.astro';
import SourceList from '../components/SourceList.astro';

const sources = [
  {
    title:
      'R. Kerry Rowe — long-term performance of geomembrane liners (HDPE service life vs temperature)',
    publisher: 'Geosynthetics / peer-reviewed engineering literature',
    date: '2020',
    note: 'Service-life range ~54 years at 60°C to several hundred years at lower temperatures. Full citation on the sources page.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Queensland landfill siting guideline — floodplain buffer requirements',
    publisher: 'Queensland Government',
    note: '100 m buffer from the 1% AEP floodplain; additional engineering required within it. URL to verify before publish.',
  },
  {
    title:
      'Victoria EPA — siting, design and management of landfills (inundation overlay guidance)',
    publisher: 'EPA Victoria',
    note: 'URL to verify before publish.',
  },
  {
    title: 'NSW EPA — Environmental Guidelines: Solid Waste Landfills',
    publisher: 'NSW Environment Protection Authority',
    note: 'URL to verify before publish.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Mayor Steve Krieg — public statement on the "mega tip" question',
    publisher: 'Facebook / Lismore City Council communications',
    date: 'September 2025',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="What's spin, what's accurate, what's missing"
  description="A four-part analysis of the public case for the Blakebrook landfill: what is accurate, what is spin, what is misleading by implication, and the major omissions — flood siting, leachate, landfill gas, buffers, post-closure care, and the waste hierarchy."
  progress
  article
>
  <PageHeader
    eyebrow="The critique"
    title="What's spin, what's accurate, what's missing"
  >
    The public case for the site has accurate parts, persuasive-but-thin parts,
    and significant gaps. We separate them so a reader — or a councillor — can
    tell which is which.
  </PageHeader>

  <article class="mx-auto max-w-prose px-5 pb-8">
    <div class="prose-body mt-10">
      <SectionDivider id="accurate">A — What&rsquo;s accurate</SectionDivider>
      <p>It is worth starting with what the council gets right:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>The need for some solution is real.</strong> Residual waste
          has to go somewhere, and the existing cell has limited life left.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Feasibility studies are a legitimate next step.</strong>{' '}
          Investigating a site before committing to it is the responsible
          sequence, not evidence of a predetermined outcome.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>NSW landfill regulation is comparatively strict.</strong> The
          state&rsquo;s solid-waste guidelines do impose real engineering and
          monitoring obligations.<SourceLink n={4} />
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Modern landfill engineering is sophisticated.</strong> A
          contemporary lined cell with leachate capture is genuinely not
          &ldquo;a hole in the ground.&rdquo;
        </li>
      </ul>

      <SectionDivider id="spin">B — What&rsquo;s spin</SectionDivider>
      <p>
        Spin is not lying. It is true-but-steering framing. Four examples:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>The &ldquo;mega tip&rdquo; defusing comparison.</strong> The
          public case contrasts 60,000 t/yr here with metro landfills taking
          200,000+ t/yr.<SourceLink n={5} /> But the relevant comparison is not
          Sydney&rsquo;s tonnage — it is the <strong
            >receiving environment</strong
          >. A modest tonnage in a high-rainfall, flood-influenced,
          surface-water-rich catchment can pose more risk than a larger tonnage
          on an arid, deep-watertable site. Tonnage alone is the wrong yardstick.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>The &ldquo;open mind&rdquo; framing.</strong> Casting critics
          as having &ldquo;closed their minds&rdquo; positions scrutiny as
          obstruction. Asking hard siting questions early is not closed-
          mindedness; it is exactly what the assessment process is for.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>The &ldquo;400 trucks is hype&rdquo; dismissal.</strong> The
          honest number is neither 400 nor zero. We work it through on the{' '}
          <a href="/numbers">numbers page</a>: roughly 13 inbound loads a day,
          and perhaps 30&ndash;50 total vehicle movements at the gate once you
          add outbound trucks, leachate tankers, cover-soil deliveries and
          staff. That is a meaningful local traffic change — worth assessing
          honestly rather than dismissing.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Equating strict regulation with zero risk.</strong> Strict
          rules reduce risk; they do not eliminate it. Regulation sets
          standards — outcomes still depend on siting, construction quality, and
          decades of maintenance.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <SectionDivider id="misleading"
        >C — What&rsquo;s inaccurate or misleading by implication</SectionDivider
      >
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>The infographic is a PR diagram, not an engineering spec.</strong
          > The &ldquo;Anatomy of a Landfill&rdquo; image attached to the
          public case is a generic United States public-relations graphic. It
          illustrates the concept of a modern landfill; it is not a design for
          this site, this geology, or this rainfall.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Liner service life depends heavily on conditions.</strong>{' '}
          HDPE geomembrane service life is strongly temperature- and
          leachate-chemistry-dependent. Rowe (2020) gives a range from roughly
          <strong>54 years at 60&deg;C</strong> to several hundred years at
          lower temperatures.<SourceLink n={1} /> &ldquo;The liner protects the
          groundwater&rdquo; is true only within that envelope.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Seams are the common failure point.</strong> Liners fail most
          often at welded seams and penetrations, not across intact sheet — which
          is why construction quality assurance matters as much as the
          specification.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Liners delay, not eliminate, migration.</strong> Even a
          perfect liner system slows contaminant transport; it does not make a
          landfill permanently inert. That is why post-closure monitoring
          exists.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <SectionDivider id="omissions">D — Major omissions</SectionDivider>
      <p>
        This is the largest concern. The questions below are standard for any
        50-year facility, and the public case has not yet answered them:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Floodplain siting.</strong> Queensland&rsquo;s guideline sets
          a 100 m buffer from the 1% AEP floodplain, with additional engineering
          required inside it.<SourceLink n={2} /> Victoria&rsquo;s EPA advises
          against siting landfills on land under a Land Subject to Inundation
          Overlay.<SourceLink n={3} /> The 2022 floods damaged the existing
          Lismore landfill. Siting a 50-year facility in any flood-influenced
          catchment in this region warrants close scrutiny.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Long-term leachate liability.</strong> Leachate carries heavy
          metals, ammonia and organic compounds. Aftercare obligations extend
          30+ years beyond closure — a liability that outlives most council
          electoral cycles.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Landfill gas.</strong> Methane and trace volatile organic
          compounds are generated for decades. Real-world capture efficiency is
          typically <strong>60&ndash;85%</strong>, not 100%.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Air quality, odour and dust.</strong> A typical buffer to
          sensitive receptors is around 500 m. Where are the nearest dwellings?
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Post-closure care.</strong> Who pays for monitoring and
          maintenance in year 31, year 50, year 75? This is a standard concern
          and it is unaddressed in the public case.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Construction quality assurance.</strong> Liners work <em
            >if</em
          > installed and inspected to specification. CQA failures are a leading
          cause of containment breaches.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>The waste hierarchy.</strong> Site selection assumes the
          question is &ldquo;where,&rdquo; not &ldquo;how much.&rdquo; We argue
          the threshold question is volume — see{' '}
          <a href="/centralised-vs-local">the model question</a>.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Alternatives.</strong> The public case has not seriously
          canvassed expansion of Nammoona, Stotts Creek, or Grafton. We set
          these out on the <a href="/alternatives">alternatives page</a>.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <PullQuote>
      Yes, we need a waste solution. Yes, studies are appropriate. But the
      threshold question is whether this site can clear standard siting criteria
      around flood risk, hydrogeology and buffers — because if it can&rsquo;t,
      no amount of engineering makes it the right place.
    </PullQuote>

    <SourceList sources={sources} />
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
